04246nam a22007695i 9789814786379DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172017si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898147863797 a10.1355/97898147863792doi  a(DE-B1597)522131  a(OCoLC)1096436783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aSOC0480002bisacsh1 aSaat, Norshahril, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Traditionalist Response to Wahhabi-Salafism in Batam /cNorshahril Saat. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (20 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tINTRODUCTION -- tTRADITIONALISM, MODERNISM, AND SALAFI-WAHHABISM -- tISLAMIC ORGANIZATIONS IN BATAM -- tBATAM MUSLIMS AND TRADITIONALISTS -- tTHE SINGAPORE DIMENSION -- tCONCLUSION: EXCLUSIVISM AND TRADITIONALISM -- tREFERENCES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rise of Wahhabi-Salafi ideology in neighbouring Batam is causing concern in Singapore. There are worries that some Singapore Muslims are being radicalized by Batam's Islamic radio station Hang FM, which openly promotes Wahhabi-Salafi teachings. The uncovering by Batam police of a plan by five Indonesians to launch a missile from the island, targeting Singapore's Marina Bay, and the arrest of some individuals linked to ISIS (Islamic State in Iraq and Syria) in Batam in August 2016 strengthen these fears. This article argues that Batam Muslims are non-violent traditionalists in their orientation, and key religious leaders from the state have come out against Wahhabi-Salafis anti-pluralist ideas. Contrary to expectations, key traditionalist practices like mass prayers (zikr), and praises to the Prophet Muhammad (selawat), which Wahhabi-Salafis frown upon, continue to attract a huge following in Batam. In contradistinction to perceptions that Batam influences Singapore, the city-state does in its own right exert influence on its neighbour, and monetary flow from Singapore Muslims help keep traditionalist rituals alive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIslamic Studies. 0aIslamic fundamentalism—Indonesia—Batam. 0aIslam—Indonesia—Batam. 0aIslam—Singapore. 0aMuslims—Indonesia—Batam. 0aMuslims—Singapore. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066298608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981478637940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814786379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814786379.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066298-6  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-071954-3  DG Plus eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK